                            <comment id="18203" author="springboy" created="Mon, 26 Jun 2006 00:20:55 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Joe&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&apos;m tempted to agree with you on this one.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It does break backward compatibility, and was added as part of the convention over configuration (CoC) functionality. The CoC functionality allows one to simply add objects to a ModelAndView and let the ModelAndView figure out the name base don a set of naming conventions. Obviously if the model object is null, then the ModelAndView cannot figure out the name, hence the exception that you are now seeing. However, if you are already supplying the name, then well, it&apos;s up to you as to whether or not you want to put a null into the ModelAndView.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Let me have a quick confer with the other Spring devs (specifically the guy who implemented the CoC support) and I&apos;ll get back to you (and hopefully this issue).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cheers&lt;br/&gt;
Rick&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18204" author="springboy" created="Mon, 26 Jun 2006 00:44:58 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Joe&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Indeed, fixed as per your request. Thanks for spotting this.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cheers&lt;br/&gt;
Rick&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18216" author="jmays" created="Mon, 26 Jun 2006 11:34:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Thanks, Rick.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We&apos;re using Spring for a rather large project at my company, and it means a lot to us that you guys are this responsive and are this concerned about backwards compatibility.  Thanks a lot for looking into this, and taking time to explain the issue.  Spring is a top-class product by every measure, and the dedication of the Spring team makes it that way.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Sincerely,&lt;br/&gt;
Joe Mays&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
